ury popular media. Focusing on the intertwining of belief and commodification, fear and pleasure, horror and humor, he illuminates different conceptions of the "natural" and the "ordinary" and sheds light on broader social and historical paradigms—and ultimately on the construction of Japan as a nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnimals, MythicalzJapan. 0aSpirits. 0aSupernatural. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aayakashi.  abelief.  acommodification.  ademons.  aeast asian cultural studies.  ahorror.  ahuman electricity.  ahumor.  ajapan.  ajapanese cultural imagination.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese folklore.  akanji.  akokkuri.  amalevolent.  amamono.  aminzokugaku.  amischievous.  amizuki shigeru.  amodernity.  amononoke.  amonsters.  amountain goblins.  anatural history.  ashape shifting animals.  aspirits.  aspooky stories.  asupernatural monsters.  atoriyama sekien.  awater sprites.  ayokai.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025361240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094267740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942677423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942677/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY